1
00:00:05,007 --> 00:00:06,488
Jīvas, what do they think?

2
00:00:06,488 --> 00:00:10,538
Classic Bengali expression,
means “crack-brained”.

3
00:00:10,743 --> 00:00:13,860
[Mind—Crazy Driver]

4
00:00:14,110 --> 00:00:18,644
Once some fellow, 
he bowed down

5
00:00:18,644 --> 00:00:22,185
to give Gurudev dandavat;
this was a long time ago.

6
00:00:22,462 --> 00:00:26,268
While he was down Gurudev went:
[gesturing to show splitting something].

7
00:00:26,268 --> 00:00:27,688
You know, [laughing]

8
00:00:27,688 --> 00:00:30,645
it means ‘cracked’; 
his brain is cracked, like a coconut.

9
00:00:30,645 --> 00:00:32,985
[gesturing to show split]

10
00:00:32,985 --> 00:00:37,093
When you’re under 
the clutches of Māyā, the witch,

11
00:00:37,093 --> 00:00:38,292
haunted by the witch of Māyā,

12
00:00:38,292 --> 00:00:40,742
it’s said, you speak
all kinds of nonsense

13
00:00:40,742 --> 00:00:42,813
like a ghostly 
haunted person.

14
00:00:42,968 --> 00:00:48,116
There’s schizophrenia
in the clinical sense,

15
00:00:48,116 --> 00:00:53,432
but this sort of dual personality …

16
00:00:54,848 --> 00:00:58,833
it’s like being crazy
within the crazy world.

17
00:00:59,380 --> 00:01:06,821
Because we’re all in varying degrees
insane, deluded,

18
00:01:08,886 --> 00:01:13,182
struggling with the senses;

19
00:01:13,182 --> 00:01:16,997
manaḥ-ṣaṣṭhānīndriyāṇi
prakṛti-sthāni karṣati 
[Bg: 15.7],

20
00:01:17,059 --> 00:01:19,202
struggling with the senses,
of which …

21
00:01:19,202 --> 00:01:22,782
Remember, we have six senses:

22
00:01:22,966 --> 00:01:26,977
the five obvious ones 
and the mind.

23
00:01:26,977 --> 00:01:30,856
And the mind is the sense
that we have the most problem with.

24
00:01:31,573 --> 00:01:34,188
Friend or enemy.

25
00:01:36,521 --> 00:01:40,220
There was a cartoon strip,

26
00:01:40,267 --> 00:01:45,903
comic strip in the 1960’s, where …

27
00:01:47,948 --> 00:01:50,836
Because it’s during the time
of the Vietnam war,

28
00:01:50,836 --> 00:01:53,157
so there’s all use 
of the word “enemy”—

29
00:01:53,157 --> 00:01:57,311
“who’s the enemy”,
and that kind of thing.

30
00:01:57,624 --> 00:02:01,139
And what was in the comic strip
was one famous line,

31
00:02:01,139 --> 00:02:04,538
where one of the characters
says to another one,

32
00:02:04,538 --> 00:02:09,901
“We have met the enemy,
and the enemy is us”,

33
00:02:11,229 --> 00:02:15,383
which is the actual truth.

34
00:02:17,034 --> 00:02:22,075
We are the enemy, the mind
that we think is our friend.

35
00:02:22,547 --> 00:02:25,554
The body is like a chariot,

36
00:02:25,554 --> 00:02:29,821
the senses are five horses,

37
00:02:29,821 --> 00:02:32,599
and the soul is like the passenger,

38
00:02:32,599 --> 00:02:38,783
and the mind is ...
like you have an insane driver,

39
00:02:38,783 --> 00:02:43,673
crazy driver, 
[laughing]

40
00:02:46,894 --> 00:02:51,016
taking you for a ride.

41
00:02:52,295 --> 00:03:01,990
So Guru Mahārāj often uses
the example of mental illness:

42
00:03:04,390 --> 00:03:09,744
deluded into thinking
you’re someone you’re not.

43
00:03:13,650 --> 00:03:16,433
So without getting
sambandha-jñān,

44
00:03:16,433 --> 00:03:19,824
a basic understanding 
of who I am,

45
00:03:19,824 --> 00:03:25,659
and what my potential is,
how can I proceed

46
00:03:25,659 --> 00:03:27,830
in a way 
that’s actually beneficial

47
00:03:27,830 --> 00:03:31,667
for my self-discovery, 
self-realisation,

48
00:03:31,667 --> 00:03:35,334
even ultimate autonomy.

49
00:03:35,334 --> 00:03:37,814
It’s only one who’s free
from the influence

50
00:03:37,814 --> 00:03:42,519
of the mind and senses,
who’s truly autonomous;

51
00:03:42,519 --> 00:03:44,929
otherwise
we’re under the influence

52
00:03:44,929 --> 00:03:47,762
of the senses, the mind.

53
00:03:48,586 --> 00:03:54,036
So have to come in connection
with a proper agent,

54
00:03:54,473 --> 00:04:01,013
who knows your identity,
your reality potential,

55
00:04:01,013 --> 00:04:07,999
and under their guidance
you can engage in self-discovery,

56
00:04:08,029 --> 00:04:12,923
self-realisation,
self-actualisation.

57
00:04:14,078 --> 00:04:19,716
Like the psychiatrist, they just 
have to bring the patient around

58
00:04:19,716 --> 00:04:24,512
to seeing things 
from that perspective—

59
00:04:24,706 --> 00:04:28,739
give up the false ego, 
the false identity,

60
00:04:28,768 --> 00:04:33,403
what Guru Mahārāj called
“acquired prejudice”.

61
00:04:34,642 --> 00:04:38,072
To become free 
from saṁskāra

62
00:04:38,072 --> 00:04:40,797
is to become free 
from acquired prejudice.

63
00:04:40,797 --> 00:04:44,111
Then, 
āścarya-vat paśyati kaścid enam,
[Bg: 2.29]

64
00:04:44,111 --> 00:04:47,918
to have a glimpse of our soul,
our self,

65
00:04:47,918 --> 00:04:53,334
our reality potential
will be astonishing, fill us with wonder

66
00:04:53,334 --> 00:05:04,007
and fuel practice, and participation,
and hope.

